Dataset migration is not a file movement problem. It is a long-term access, audit, and compute strategy decision. The discussion exposes three competing objectives: speed of migration, audit defensibility, and future usability.

1. Core Decision Axis

The team is implicitly choosing between:
	•	Physical portability (Excel / raw SAS files)
	•	Analytical usability (Parquet)
	•	Operational simplicity (minimal transformation during migration)

These cannot be optimized simultaneously.

⸻

2. Format-Level Implications

Parquet (Target-state aligned)
	•	Columnar storage → efficient scans for large datasets
	•	Compression → reduces storage footprint significantly
	•	Native compatibility with Python (pandas, PySpark), SQL engines, and Trino
	•	Schema preservation → critical for regulatory reproducibility
	•	Supports partitioning → enables scalable processing

Constraint:
	•	Requires upfront conversion effort
	•	Needs schema discipline during conversion

⸻

Excel (Transit convenience, not a system of record)
	•	Easy for business users to inspect
	•	Minimal transformation effort during migration

Failure modes:
	•	No schema enforcement
	•	Type ambiguity (dates, nulls, numeric precision)
	•	Not scalable (file size, memory limits)
	•	No audit lineage or reproducibility guarantees

Conclusion: Excel introduces irreversible data degradation in a regulated pipeline.

⸻

Raw SAS datasets (deferred risk)
	•	Preserves original structure
	•	No immediate conversion effort

Critical flaw:
	•	Post-SAS decommission → loss of native readability
	•	Python access depends on libraries like pyreadstat → not guaranteed for:
	•	full metadata fidelity
	•	large-scale performance
	•	audit defensibility

This creates future access risk, not just technical debt.

⸻

3. Hidden Constraint: Regulatory and Audit Requirements

Given the context (SOX, IFRS9, AML-type workloads):
	•	Data must be:
	•	reproducible
	•	schema-consistent
	•	queryable without proprietary dependencies
	•	Transformation logic must be traceable

Implication:
	•	Any format that loses schema or requires proprietary runtime (SAS) is non-compliant long term.

⸻

4. Migration Strategy (Implied but not formalized)

A viable architecture emerges:

Tier 1: Critical datasets (active pipelines)
	•	Convert → Parquet
	•	Register in metadata layer (Hive Metastore if using Trino)
	•	Store in S3 with partitioning strategy
	•	Enforce schema validation during conversion

Tier 2: Informational datasets (audit / rarely accessed)
Two options:

Option A (safe):
	•	Convert to Parquet once
	•	Store compressed in S3
	•	Minimal cost increase, eliminates future dependency risk

Option B (risky, current team inclination):
	•	Store as-is (SAS files)
	•	Accept:
	•	future conversion complexity
	•	potential inability to read without SAS
	•	audit friction

⸻

5. Conversion Pipeline Requirements

A compliant migration requires:
	•	Schema extraction from SAS
	•	Explicit datatype mapping (no inference)
	•	Null handling standardization
	•	Date format normalization
	•	Row count + checksum validation (SAS vs Parquet)
	•	Logging of:
	•	source file
	•	conversion logic
	•	output location
	•	validation metrics

This aligns with existing audit expectations already discussed in the program.

⸻

6. Performance and Cost Tradeoff
	•	Parquet reduces storage footprint (often 3–10x compression)
	•	Enables pushdown queries → reduces compute cost
	•	Eliminates repeated conversion overhead during audits

Excel / raw SAS:
	•	Cheap now
	•	Expensive later (reprocessing, re-validation, audit reconstruction)

⸻

7. Failure Pattern in Current Discussion

Observed anti-pattern:
	•	Optimizing for migration speed
	•	Ignoring post-SAS survivability

This creates a deferred failure:
	•	At SAS shutdown → data becomes operationally unusable or requires emergency conversion under audit pressure
